(
<figureCitation id="135DFE86FF98FF80FBDFFA7DB9A66EAB" box="[1101,1166,1427,1453]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[132,143,1962,1980]" captionTargetBox="[159,1435,215,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-20@8.[140,1448,203,1942]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 4. — Begonia harimalalae Scherber. &amp; Duruiss., sp. nov.: A, habit; B, leaf, adaxial side; C, male flower, front view; D, male flower, side view; E, androecium; F, female flower, face view; G, female flower, side view; H, gynoecium; I, styles and stigmas; J, gynoecium, early fruiting stage; K, ovary cross-section. Drawn from living plant, Scherberich 1153 (Drawing: Vanessa Damianthe). Scale bars: A, B, 1 cm; C, D, F-H, J, K, 2 mm; E, I, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4602167" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4602167/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD9E203FF98FF80FCBFFA38B9876D51" blockId="7.[811,1457,1493,1623]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicName id="4C669980FF98FF80FCBFFA38B9926EEB" authority="Scherber. &amp; Duruiss." authorityName="Scherber. &amp; Duruiss." authorityYear="2019" box="[813,1210,1493,1517]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="harimalalae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B9123E11FF98FF80FCBFFA38BEC16EEB" box="[813,1001,1493,1517]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">Begonia harimalalae</emphasis>
Scherber. &amp; Duruiss.
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A221836AFF98FF80FB53FA3BB8246EEA" box="[1217,1292,1493,1516]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be compared to 
<taxonomicName id="4C669980FF98FF80FCDAFA1EBE996D01" box="[840,945,1520,1543]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="erminea">
<emphasis id="B9123E11FF98FF80FCDAFA1EBE996D01" box="[840,945,1520,1543]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">B. erminea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but it differs by the much thicker, more numerous (3-8 vs 2-5) and larger (10-15 vs 
<quantity id="4C9E4FE6FF98FF80FBF6F9E4B9816D24" box="[1124,1193,1546,1570]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" unit="cm" value="6.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="4.0">4-8 cm</quantity>
) leaves, which are glabrous, without spiculiform hairs adaxially and with the margins shallowly and sparsely serrate vs densely biserrate.
</paragraph>
